entry.title: [ChromeSigninIntercept] Fix avatar toolbar button showing name bug
entry.content:
As a result of b:301386027, the avatar toolbar button was sometimes blinking back and forth between displaying the profile name and not.

This was due to a logic error which was caused through the removal of

the enum value IdentityAnimationState::kWaitingForImage.

The CL adds the value and its check again.

With this, `IdentityAnimationState::kWaitingForImage` is only set in

`OnUserIdentityChanged`. Checking this state before showing the

animation ensures it is only shown if the user identity has changed.

entry.title: Reland "Add SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings to field trial config"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit bfe9bb7ec091d71d6925526098f9d74fd0cb048a



The CL was reverted (crrev.com/c/5046251) because the test failed on

in the browser_tests_no_field_trial target. As the name suggest, in

this (apparently existing) target, the field trial config and hence

SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings remained disabled. The test however

enabled SyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode, leading to a

feature combination that in practice is not possible (

SyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode is conditioned on and will

be launched prior to SyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings).



This caused the test to fail, because as of crrev.com/c/5023899:

- `syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode` is true

- `has_autofill_sync_type` is false, since AUTOFILL_PROFILE is

not running (and not able to run) in transport mode.

Consequently, `syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode &&

!has_autofill_sync_type` became true, preventing credit card server

saves.



This CL fixes this problem by explicitly enabling both features in the

test in question.

entry.title: partition_alloc: Drop GN targets not supporting MSVC.
entry.content:
This patch wraps most targets inside the "is_clang_or_gcc" condition.

This causes non-chrome dependents to stop building thme.



This has the nice side effect of delimiting clearly to developers

where partition_alloc's MSVC support is required and where it isn't.



Context:

--------

Even if some partition_alloc dependents only uses the "raw_ptr" target,

GN will include build them all as part of the "all" pseudo-target. Some fail are

causing [errors].



Note: I don't think it exists a GN equivalent to CMake's

"EXCLUDE_FROM_ALL" option.

entry.title: Revert "Deflake and reenable `ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle` test."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8f21a9e763ea281e391e2d7230a591bbcb9ef6d6.



Reason for revert: This test start failing consistently on https://ci.chromium.org/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Tests%20%28dbg%29%281%29 starting from https://ci.chromium.org/ui/b/8763769311537890929



Original change's description:

> Deflake and reenable `ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle` test.

>

> The

> `DynamicScriptsTrackerBrowserTest.ContentScriptViaScriptingApiWhileIdle`

> test injects a content script at `document_idle` time. The test has

> been flakily timing out while waiting until the content script signals

> that is has been run (test logs from the bots show that the test was

> timing out during the `catcher.GetNextResult()` call).

>

> Based on reading the code it seems that:

>

> * The test properly waits for `DidFinishNavigation` for the navigation

> in the main frame.

> * The test properly controls the timing of the `onload` event for one of

> the subframes. The affected subframe is one of two subframes and the

> `ControllableHttpResponse` somewhat randomly catches one or the other.

> This is okay though - the `onload` event won't happen until *both*

> subframes have finished navigating.

>

> Based on the above, it seems that the content script should indeed get

> injected at `document_idle` time - after the `onload` event. Based on

> reading additional test code, it seems that the problem is that the

> content script *also* tries to wait for the `onload` event - this

> doesn't take into the account that this event might have already been

> raised.

>

> Based on the above this CL:

>

> * Attempts to speculatively fix the flakiness, by removing the

> `window.onload = function()` part of the content script

> * Removes the secondary and ultimately unnecessary test assertions

> around `document.readyState` (which changes around `onload` event)

> * Reenables the test

> * Adds additional `console.log` statements to the content script

> to help with diagnosing any remaining flakiness (if any; we

> speculatively assume that the test should not be flaky going forward).

>

entry.title: [Files]: Separating callback from other parameters.
entry.content:
RecentSource uses an approach where parameters given to GetRecentFiles

are stored in the optional field. That field is reset when the recent

source is done with collecting files. If it is done because the scan

finished, this is fine. If it is done because the timeout occurred, it

is possible that whoever holds to those params gets a null pointer,

which causes a crash.



This CL moves the callback argument out of params. This was what caused

the params to be forced to be move-only type. By moving callback out we

can make the params a copyable object. Thus early termination of the

slow will not empty the params for stragglers.

entry.title: Mention the git longpaths support for Windows
entry.content:
By default git is constrained to the 260-character MAX_PATH limitation

on Windows. However this limitation can be configured away with this

command:



git config --global core.longpaths true



This is useful when cloning a repo that contains long paths, or if your

repo root has a longer path than expected.



Trivia: even with this configured the longest repo root path is around

210 characters. Any longer than that and "fatal: '$GIT_DIR' too big"

will be hit.



This issue was first hit and was initially tested with

"fetch infra_internal" but could hit elsewhere.



Testing has confirmed that this config setting lets git handle repos

and repo base paths that it otherwise fails on. Setting the

LongPathsEnabled registry key, in contrast, does not work.

entry.title: [drivefs] Pass expiration_time with access token on request
entry.content:
The access token passed to DriveFS is currently used all the way up

until an unauthenticated error is returned from Drive API, then it is

refreshed. This accounts for ~1% of errors, however, we can do better by

proactively refreshing the auth token just before its expiry period.



To do this, pass the expiration_time through to drivefs which will

allow existing logic the ability to proactively request a new access

token back via GetAccessToken. The expiration_time field sent back on

the signin::AccessTokenInfo already has a 10% error margin built in so

we don't have to change that time and simply send it as is.

entry.title: Add new HTTPS-First Mode tri-state settings UI
entry.content:
This adds a new radio-button selection UI for the different HTTPS-First

Mode settings (fully enabled, enabled in Incognito, and fully disabled)

to chrome://settings/security, when the HttpsFirstModeIncognito feature

is enabled. This changes the previous single SettingsToggleButton row in

the "Advanced" section with a new row (with updated setting title and

subtitle) and a SettingsRadioGroup with ControlledRadioButton elements

for each of the setting states.



This also updates the tests in security_page_test.ts to test both the

new UI (in the "Main" test) and the previous single-toggle UI (in the

"FlagsDisabled" test).



Followup CLs will connect the new UI to the "HttpsOnlyMode" enterprise

policy so that the enterprise policy indicator correctly displays, and

so the "disallowed" policy setting correctly disables HTTPS-First Mode

entirely (including in Incognito).

entry.title: Split TestAcceptDialogCallback into two to better match prod behavior
entry.content:
TestAcceptDialogCallback was used in FetchManifestAndInstall in several

tests and it hides the fact that the dialog is normally responsible for

setting the UserDisplayMode which in turn affects whether the app is

opened in a window, using display modes from the manifest. Despite tests

using OMNIBOX_INSTALL_ICON, they were installing with UDM::kBrowser.



Ideally we make test behavior match prod behavior better so it's tested.

This CL takes a step toward that by explicitly setting the UDM during

the dialog callback in tests. It also fixes some tests that were broken

by the app popping into a separate window when installed.

entry.title: [Extensions] Immediately unregister service workers on deactivation
entry.content:
On extension deactivation, we unregister the service worker at the

extension's origin. It's important that this happen immediately;

if it doesn't, it may race with a re-registration if the extension is

being reloaded, as in the case of an extension update. However,

ServiceWorkerContext::UnregisterServiceWorker() won't unregister the

worker if it has active controllees.



Typically, there are no active controllees, since we close extension

pages when unloading the extension. However, there are some exceptions

to this, such as overridden NTPs.



Fix this by adding a new method,

ServiceWorkerContext::UnregisterServiceWorkerImmediately(), which

unregisters the worker regardless of if it has controllees (this

mechanism already exists; it just wasn't exposed).



This fixes a bug where extensions could have mismatched service worker

versions in edge-case scenarios.
